('LOC_PEDIA_RELIGIONS_PAGE_SDG_TZEVAOT_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1', 'Tzevaot means "armies" and Elohe Tzevaot is a Jewish name for God that translates to "the Lord of Heaven''s armies" or "the God of the armies of Israel". In the King James Version these are usually translated as "Lord of Hosts". While not common in the Torah, this name of God is frequently used in the books of the prophets as the writers are trying to persuade their followers to remain loyal to the one who is truly powerful in the face of the armies of the Assyrians and Babylonians who were conquering their lands and forcing them into exile.', 'en_US'),

