('LOC_PEDIA_RELIGIONS_PAGE_SDG_SLAVE_SPIRITUALS_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1', 'Spirituals are Christian songs that were created by enslaved African Americans. Originally they were an oral tradition that imparted Christian values while also describing the hardships of slavery. Although spirituals were originally unaccompanied unison songs, they are best known today in harmonized choral arrangements.', 'en_US'),



('LOC_SDG_NEARER_MY_GOD', 'Nearer, My God, to Thee', 'en_US'),
('LOC_SDG_NEARER_MY_GOD_DESCRIPTION', '+1[ICON_Amenities]Amenity[NEWLINE][in cities that follow this religion]', 'en_US'),
('LOC_PEDIA_RELIGIONS_PAGE_SDG_NEARER_MY_GOD_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1', '"Nearer, My God, to Thee" is a 19th-century Christian hymn by Sarah Flower Adams that retells the story of Jacob''s dream. Genesis 28:11-12 can be translated as follows: "So he came to a certain place and stayed there all night, because the sun had set. And he took one of the stones of that place and put it at his head, and he lay down in that place to sleep. Then he dreamed, and behold, a ladder was set up on the earth, and its top reached to heaven; and there the angels of God were ascending and descending on it..."[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]The hymn is often used at the funerals of U.S. Presidents and was the alleged last song the band on RMS Titanic played before the ship sank.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]CNN''s founder Ted Turner, at the launch of the channel in 1980, promised: "We won''t be signing off until the world ends. ... We''ll be ... covering it live. ... [And] when the end of the world comes, we''ll play ''Nearer My God to Thee'' before we sign off." Turner commissioned a video recording of the hymn for this purpose, played by a military marching band, which he sometimes played for reporters. In 2015, the video, tagged in CNN''s database as "[Hold for release] till end of world confirmed", was leaked on the Internet.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]1 Nearer, my God, to thee, nearer to thee! [NEWLINE]E''en though it be a cross that raiseth me, [NEWLINE]still all my song shall be, [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee; [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee, nearer to thee! [NEWLINE][NEWLINE]2 Though like the wanderer, the sun gone down, [NEWLINE]darkness be over me, my rest a stone; [NEWLINE]yet in my dreams I''d be [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee; [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee, nearer to thee! [NEWLINE][NEWLINE]3 There let the way appear, steps unto heaven; [NEWLINE]all that thou sendest me, in mercy given; [NEWLINE]angels to beckon me [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee; [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee, nearer to thee! [NEWLINE][NEWLINE]4 Then, with my waking thoughts bright with thy praise, [NEWLINE]out of my stony griefs Bethel I''ll raise; [NEWLINE]so by my woes to be [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee; [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee, nearer to thee! [NEWLINE][NEWLINE]5 Or if, on joyful wing cleaving the sky, [NEWLINE]sun, moon, and stars forgot, upward I fly, [NEWLINE]still all my song shall be, [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee; [NEWLINE]nearer, my God, to thee, nearer to thee!', 'en_US'),

