('LOC_PEDIA_RELIGIONS_PAGE_SDG_BE_STILL_MY_SOUL_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1', 'The Christian hymn "Be still, my soul", written in German in 1752 by Katharina Amalia Dorothea von Schlegel (1697-1768) and translated into English in 1855 by Jane Laurie Borthwick (1813-1897), is usually sung to the tune "Finlandia" by Finnish composer Jean Sibelius.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]1 Be still, my soul: the Lord is on thy side;[NEWLINE]bear patiently the cross of grief or pain;[NEWLINE]leave to thy God to order and provide;[NEWLINE]in ev''ry change He faithful will remain.[NEWLINE]Be still, my soul: thy best, thy heav''nly Friend[NEWLINE]thro'' thorny ways leads to a joyful end.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]2 Be still, my soul: thy God doth undertake[NEWLINE]to guide the future as He has the past.[NEWLINE]Thy hope, thy confidence let nothing shake;[NEWLINE]all now mysterious shall be bright at last.[NEWLINE]Be still, my soul: the waves and winds still know[NEWLINE]His voice, who ruled them while He dwelt below.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]3 Be still, my soul: when dearest friends depart,[NEWLINE]and all is darkened in the veil of tears,[NEWLINE]then shalt thou better know His love, His heart,[NEWLINE]who comes to soothe thy sorrow and thy fears.[NEWLINE]Be still, my soul: thy Jesus can repay[NEWLINE]from His own fullness all He takes away.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]4 Be still, my soul: the hour is hast''ning on[NEWLINE]when we shall be forever with the Lord,[NEWLINE]when disappointment, grief, and fear are gone,[NEWLINE]sorrow forgot, love''s purest joys restored.[NEWLINE]Be still, my soul: when change and tears are past,[NEWLINE]all safe and blessed we shall meet at last.', 'en_US'),

('LOC_SDG_ODE_TO_JOY', 'Ode to Joy', 'en_US'),
('LOC_SDG_ODE_TO_JOY_DESCRIPTION', '+1[ICON_Amenities]Amenity for every 2 specialty districts[NEWLINE][in cities that follow this religion]', 'en_US'),
('LOC_PEDIA_RELIGIONS_PAGE_SDG_ODE_TO_JOY_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1', '"Ode to Joy" is an ode written by Friedrich Schiller and put to music by Ludwig van Beethoven in the final movement of his Ninth Symphony. The premiere took place in Vienna on May 7, 1824, and despite its unpracticed and under-rehearsed presentation, the audience was ecstatic. At the end of the performance, it was said that Beethoven continued conducting even though the music had ended. One of the soloists stopped him and turned him around to accept his applause. The audience was aware of Beethoven''s health and hearing loss, so in addition to clapping, they threw their hats and scarves in the air so that he could see their overwhelming approval.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]This symphony is considered by many leading musicologists to be one of the greatest works in western music. It was the first symphony by a major composer to include the human voice and required an orchestra bigger than any other at the time. The premier was a major turning point for classical music, igniting the Romantic Period, where composers began breaking the rules of composition and exploring the use of large ensembles, extreme emotion, and unconventional orchestration. The tune for the "Ode to Joy" section of the symphony was adopted as the Anthem of Europe by the Council of Europe in 1972 and subsequently by the European Union.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]O friends, no more of these sounds![NEWLINE]Let us sing more cheerful songs,[NEWLINE]More songs full of joy![NEWLINE]Joy![NEWLINE]Joy![NEWLINE]Joy, bright spark of divinity,[NEWLINE]Daughter of Elysium,[NEWLINE]Fire-inspired we tread[NEWLINE]Within thy sanctuary.[NEWLINE]Thy magic power re-unites[NEWLINE]All that custom has divided,[NEWLINE]All men become brothers,[NEWLINE]Under the sway of thy gentle wings.[NEWLINE]Whoever has created[NEWLINE]An abiding friendship,[NEWLINE]Or has won[NEWLINE]A true and loving wife,[NEWLINE]All who can call at least one soul theirs,[NEWLINE]Join our song of praise;[NEWLINE]But those who cannot must creep tearfully[NEWLINE]Away from our circle.[NEWLINE]All creatures drink of joy[NEWLINE]At natures breast.[NEWLINE]Just and unjust[NEWLINE]Alike taste of her gift;[NEWLINE]She gave us kisses and the fruit of the vine,[NEWLINE]A tried friend to the end.[NEWLINE]Even the worm can feel contentment,[NEWLINE]And the cherub stands before God![NEWLINE]Gladly, like the heavenly bodies[NEWLINE]Which He sent on their courses[NEWLINE]Through the splendor of the firmament;[NEWLINE]Thus, brothers, you should run your race,[NEWLINE]Like a hero going to victory![NEWLINE]You millions, I embrace you.[NEWLINE]This kiss is for all the world![NEWLINE]Brothers, above the starry canopy[NEWLINE]There must dwell a loving father.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Do you fall in worship, you millions?[NEWLINE]World, do you know your creator?[NEWLINE]Seek Him in the heavens;[NEWLINE]Above the stars must he dwell.', 'en_US'),

('LOC_SDG_HALLELUJAH_CHORUS', 'Hallelujah Chorus', 'en_US'),
('LOC_SDG_HALLELUJAH_CHORUS_DESCRIPTION', '+1[ICON_Amenities]Amenity from [ICON_DISTRICT_HOLYSITE]Holy Sites and +1[ICON_Faith]Faith from land/water[ICON_DISTRICT_ENTERTAINMENT]Entertainment Complexes. Double if the districts are adjacent.[NEWLINE][in cities that follow this religion]', 'en_US'),
('LOC_PEDIA_RELIGIONS_PAGE_SDG_HALLELUJAH_CHORUS_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1', '"Messiah" is an English-language oratorio composed in 1741 by George Frideric Handel. It was first performed in Dublin on April 13, 1742, and received its London premiere nearly a year later. After an initially modest public reception, the oratorio gained in popularity, eventually becoming one of the best-known and most frequently performed choral works in Western music.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Handel''s reputation in England, where he had lived since 1712, had been established through his compositions of Italian opera. He turned to English oratorio in the 1730s in response to changes in public taste; Messiah was his sixth work in this genre. Although its structure resembles that of opera, it is not in dramatic form; there are no impersonations of characters and no direct speech. Instead, the text is an extended reflection on Jesus as the Messiah called Christ. The text begins in Part I with prophecies by Isaiah and others, and moves to the annunciation to the shepherds, the only scene taken from the Gospels. In Part II, Handel concentrates on the Passion and ends with the "Hallelujah" chorus. In Part III he covers the resurrection of the dead and Christ''s glorification in heaven.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah[NEWLINE]Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]For the lord God omnipotent reigneth[NEWLINE]Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah[NEWLINE]For the lord God omnipotent reigneth[NEWLINE]Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah[NEWLINE]For the lord God omnipotent reigneth (Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]For the lord God omnipotent reigneth (Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah (Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]For the lord God omnipotent reigneth (Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]Hallelujah[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]The kingdom of this world[NEWLINE]Is become[NEWLINE]The kingdom of our Lord,[NEWLINE]And of His Christ[NEWLINE]And of His Christ[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]And He shall reign forever and ever[NEWLINE]And He shall reign forever and ever (And He shall reign forever and ever)[NEWLINE]And He shall reign forever and ever (And He shall reign forever and ever)[NEWLINE]And he shall reign forever and ever (And He shall reign forever and ever)[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]King of kings (Forever and ever hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]And lord of lords (Forever and ever hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]King of kings (Forever and ever hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]And lord of lords (Forever and ever hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]King of kings (Forever and ever hallelujah hallelujah)[NEWLINE]And lord of lords[NEWLINE]King of kings and lord of lords[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]And he shall reign forever and ever (And he shall reign)[NEWLINE]And he shall reign forever and ever (And he shall reign)[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]King of kings forever and ever[NEWLINE]And lord of lords hallelujah hallelujah[NEWLINE]And he shall reign forever, forever and ever[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]King of kings and lord of lords[NEWLINE]King of kings and lord of lords[NEWLINE]And he shall reign forever and ever (And he shall reign forever and ever)[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Forever and ever, forever and ever (King of kings and lord of lords)[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah hallelujah[NEWLINE]Hallelujah', 'en_US'),



('LOC_SDG_KOSHER_FOOD', 'Kosher Food', 'en_US'),
